<DOC><DOCNO> AP890831-0223 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-89 0136EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     08-31 0802</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0841</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Americans' personal incomes rose a brisk 0.7percent in July while consumer spending also rose 0.7 percent, thefastest growth since April, the government says.   The Commerce Department also made significant revisions Wednesdayto previous months' figures, showing that income growth and consumerspending were not as sluggish as previously believed.   The growth in income, fueled by rapid growth in wages andsalaries, was the biggest monthly gain since March.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Federal disclosure rules taking effect todaywill make it easier to shop for a credit card, fostering competitionthat could lower interest rates for the nation's 107 millioncardholders.   The regulations require credit card issuers to disclose theinterest rate, monthly fee, grace period and other terms in a charton the application used to sign up customers.   Until now, companies have not had to disclose a card's costsuntil it arrived in the mail, under federal regulations. However, adozen states have their own disclosure rules.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Exxon Corp. has named marine scientist John H.Steele as a director, in response to shareholder demands for theaddition of an environmental expert following the nation's worst oilspill.   Steele, 62, is president and a senior scientist at Woods HoleOceanographic Institution. He also will serve on the board's newlyformed public issues committee, which will monitor the company'senvironmental policies, Exxon said Wednesday.</TEXT><DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A group of franchisees operating more than 500Arby's fast-food restaurants has offered over $200 million for thechain, but the owner says it's not interested in selling.   Arby's Inc. is owned by a company controlled by DWG Corp., aMiami-based holding company controlled by industrialist VictorPosner.   The group of eight franchisees said Wednesday that Posner's legaland financial problems could threaten the stability of Arby's.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Leona Helmsley, the persnickety hotel queenquoted as saying ``only the little people pay taxes,'' has beenconvicted of evading $1.2 million in income tax by charging personalexpenses to her business empire.   The federal jury on Wednesday acquitted Mrs. Helmsley, 69, of themost serious charge against her, conspiring to extort payoffs fromvendors.   Defense lawyers said Mrs. Helmsley was the victim of spitefulex-employees.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A lawsuit filed by a founder of Kohlberg KravisRoberts andamp; Co. shows dissension in the ranks of the leveraged buyoutfirm, which has done some of the biggest corporate takeovers of alltime.   Jerome Kohlberg Jr. filed suit Tuesday in state Supreme Court inManhattan alleging that the firm reduced his stake in severalcompanies that were acquired when he was one of its general partners.   The suit names as defendants Kohlberg Kravis, its KKR Associatesarm and the firm's two other founders, Henry R. Kravis and George R.Roberts.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., the Wall Streetgiant that recently settled federal securities fraud charges, hasannounced several senior management changes, including theappointment of a new president.   The company said Wednesday that Howard Brenner, 56, the seniorexecutive vice president, will succeed Joseph A. Vitanza, 65, whohas held the presidency since 1982.   Vitanza plans to retire Dec. 31 and will remain a consultant tothe brokerage firm.</TEXT><DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Eastern Airlines, nearing the seventh month of itsstrike, says it will add another 101 daily flights Oct. 1 and isahead of its rebuilding schedule.   The announcement Wednesday of new flights, mostly between Floridaand Northeast cities, came a day before Eastern officials werescheduled to make a presentation in New York to creditors.   The Wall Street Journal said Eastern faces $400 million inrevenue shortfalls.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Texas Air Corp. Chairman Frank Lorenzo has metwith Donald J. Trump in an effort to persuade the New York developerto buy Continental Airlines, a Trump associate says.   But Trump has concerns about a potential purchase of Continental,a subsidiary of Texas Air, including Continental's $2.5 billiondebt, its small cash reserves and the need to refurbish many of itsplanes, Bruce Nobles, president of Trump Shuttle, said Wednesday.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The stock market ended modestly higher after abouncy session Wednesday. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrialsfinished ahead by 1.52 points at 2,728.15.   The dollar rose sharply. Bond prices edged upward in a lacklustersession. Copper futures prices rebounded on news of a strike vote byworkers at a Chilean Copper Corp. mine, but gains were tempered byreports that labor troubles elsewhere may be easing. Frozen porkbelly prices remained strong, cattle and hog prices were mostlylower, wheat futures fell, corn and soybeans were mixed, preciousmetals declined and oil futures rallied.</TEXT></DOC>